In 1852 it had an area of 1,536,000 acres (6,220 km ) and was described as being mountainous with fertile plains.
Auckland County was named in honour of George Eden , who was the First Earl of Auckland between (1784-1849).
^ Geographical Names Board of NSW ^ "Old Welsh Books with English Translations" , The Land of Gold: the Companion for the Welsh Emigrant to Australia , 1852

Auckland County, New South Wales is one of the 141 Cadastral divisions of New South Wales . It is at the extreme south-east of the state, with the Victorian border to the south, and the area to the north of the Brogo River the boundary to the north. It includes Bega , Eden and Merimbula
